ined and often-ignored segment of the union movement and expands our knowledge of working men and women, the institutions they formed, and the organizational obstacles they faced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aCollective bargainingxGovernment employeeszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGovernment employee unionszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150170748340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501707483423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501707483/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles